  "query": "B2B SaaS case study structure — three-act narrative, customer hero, quantified business outcome, common case study failure modes, headline writing for case studies",
  "text": "## The structure that actually works\n\nMost case studies fail before the reader gets past the headline. Not because the story is bad, but because the structure buries the customer and centers the vendor. Flip that, and everything changes.\n\nThe three-act structure that holds up across B2B SaaS looks like this:\n\n**Act 1: The world before.** Name the specific problem. Not \"they needed better visibility\" but \"the finance team was manually reconciling 14 spreadsheets every close cycle and still missing errors.\" The more specific the pain, the more the right reader leans in and thinks *that's us.*\n\n**Act 2: The moment of change.** This is where your product enters, but briefly. The customer chose you, implemented, and something shifted. Keep this act short. It's the bridge, not the destination.\n\n**Act 3: The world after.** This is where you spend most of your words. What does the customer's life look like now? What can they do that they couldn't before? This is the superpower act.\n\n---\n\n## The customer is the hero. Full stop.\n\nThe most common failure mode: the vendor becomes the protagonist. \"Our platform's AI-powered workflow engine reduced...\" Wrong. The customer reduced. The customer achieved. The customer transformed.\n\nThink about what a case study is really doing for a skeptical B2B buyer. They're not reading to learn about your features. They're reading to see themselves in the story. \"Is this company like me? Did they have my problem? Did it actually work?\" Every sentence should serve that recognition moment.\n\nThe case study about online scheduling software that helps the front desk *and* reduces costs for the CFO *and* improves patient satisfaction? That's the model. Show value to multiple stakeholders in the org, because in complex B2B deals, multiple people are reading your case study with different questions.\n\n---\n\n## Quantified outcomes: the specificity rule\n\n\"Significant time savings\" is worthless. \"Reduced close cycle from 12 days to 4\" is a headline.\n\nThe specificity rule: **one number beats three adjectives every time.** If you can get the customer to share hard numbers, that's your headline. If you can't, get a time metric, a headcount metric, or a before/after comparison. Something the reader can picture and translate to their own situation.\n\nWatch out for the percentage trap. \"Improved efficiency by 40%\" means nothing without context. \"Cut manual reporting from 8 hours weekly to 45 minutes\" means everything.\n\n---\n\n## Headline writing\n\nYour headline has one job: make the right reader stop scrolling. The formula that works:\n\n**[Customer type] + [Specific outcome] + [Time or scale context]**\n\n\"How a 200-person fintech cut month-end close from 12 days to 4 without adding headcount\" beats \"Customer Success Story: Acme Corp\" by a mile.\n\nThe failure mode here is writing a headline that could apply to any vendor. \"Acme Corp Achieves Operational Excellence with [Your Product]\" tells the reader nothing and makes you sound like every other case study on G2.\n\n---\n\n## The failure modes worth naming\n\n- **Leading with company background.** Nobody cares that your customer \"is a leading provider of...\" Get to the problem in sentence one.\n- **Vague attribution.** \"The team loved the platform\" from an unnamed VP of Something is not social proof. Name, title, company. Let the quote do real work.\n- **Skipping the before state.** Without a vivid before, the after has no weight. The contrast is the story.\n- **One stakeholder, one lens.** In B2B, the economic buyer, the end user, and the champion all read differently. A case study that speaks to all three is three times as useful for sales.\n\nWhich part of this are you building right now: the story structure, the headline, or the quote/data capture process?",
